body:
I'm trying to use React on server-side on a Java project.
Unfortunately we're tied on jdk 1.6 for this project so we can't use Nashorn. Since jdk 1.6 has it's own JavascriptEngine I thought it was good enough to give it a shot.
Everything was fine until I tried to render a component with more than one children. Whenever a component has more than one children React renders them randomly.

Here's is a simple test case.

``` java
import java.io.FileReader;

import javax.script.ScriptEngine;
import javax.script.ScriptEngineManager;

public class Test {
    private ScriptEngine se;

    // Constructor, sets up React and the Component
    public Test() throws Throwable {
        ScriptEngineManager sem = new ScriptEngineManager();
        se = sem.getEngineByName("JavaScript");
        // React depends on the "global" variable
        se.eval("var global = this");

        // polyfill
        se.eval(new FileReader("es5-shim.js"));
        se.eval(new FileReader("es5-sham.js"));
        // eval react.js
        se.eval(new FileReader("react-0.13.1.min.js"));
        // This would also be an external JS file

        String component = ""
                + "var BackButton = React.createClass({"
                + "render: function() {"
                + "return ("
                + "React.createElement(\"a\", {href: this.props.url, className: \"Button BackButton\"}, \"first\", \"second\", this.props.text)"
                + ")}});";

        se.eval(component);
    }

    // Render the component, which can be called multiple times
    public String render(String text) throws Throwable {
        String render = "React.renderToString(React.createFactory(BackButton)({"
                + " text: '" + text + "'," + " url: 'www.google.com'" + "}))";

        return se.eval(render).toString();
    }

    public static void main(String args[]) {
        try {
              Test t2 = new Test(); 
              System.out.println(t2.render("third"));
        } catch (Throwable e) {
              System.out.println("e: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }

}
```

Given this example React.renderToString generates the following markup:

``` html
<a class="Button BackButton" href="www.google.com" data-reactid=".1cxxsje631f" data-react-checksum="-305574598">
    <span data-reactid=".1cxxsje631f.1">second</span>
    <span data-reactid=".1cxxsje631f.2">third</span>
    <span data-reactid=".1cxxsje631f.0">first</span>
</a>
```

Spent some time yesterday and today trying to figure this out. Narrowed things down until I reach `ReactReconciler.mountComponent`. For some reason children are being called on `second`,`third`,`first` order.

Appreciate any help help or ideas for what could be causing this.
